user:
Sure — here’s a small CSS addition that will automatically adjust the page when a visitor’s device is in dark‑mode, while keeping your “Ocean” tone calm and readable.

---

### 🌙 Add this inside the same `<style>` block

```css
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  body {
    background-color: #1F2E33;    /* charcoal‑blue */
    color: #E8E8E8;               /* off‑white text */
  }
  h1, h3 { color: #BFE9E0; }      /* soft‑mint headings */
  a { color: #FFB4A2; }           /* gentle coral links */
  code, pre {
    background: #25393A;          /* muted teal box */
    color: #E8E8E8;
  }
  footer {
    border-top: 1px solid #2A7F8C;
    color: #BFE9E0;
  }
}
```

---

This snippet listens for the user’s system preference and swaps to a darker background, keeping the mint and coral accents visible without glare.  
The **988** and **findahelpline.com** details will still stand out because the coral hue remains readable on the dark backdrop.

